div.p:
               Paul in the conclusion of his epistle to the Hebrues, saith, I beseech you brethren suffer the word of exhortation;
               Heb. 13.22
               for I haue written a letter to you in few words (few indeed) in comparison of the waightinesse, and excellency of the matter) so say I to you, I beseech you brethren and sisters in the Lord, suffer the word of correction, and reproofe (though wicked men will not be rebuked,
               Pro. 9.7.8. Math. 7.6.
               and scorners hate to be corrected euen by word of mouth) for I haue vsed few words in comparison of that which the greatnesse and commonnesse of this sinne doth require at my hands;

                  Esto crudita. Gen. 20.16 and (as Abimelec said to Sara) Let euery one of vs be reproued, that are guilty of this most wicked maumetry & dotage vpō our selues or others, in respect of any outward gift or ornament whatsoeuer, seperated

from the inward graces of sanctification and godly life. The Prophet Hosea (who liued in the same Kings daies that Esaiah did) complaining of the desperate estate of the Israelites,
Esay. 1.1. Hose. 1.1. telleth them That whoredom & wine,
               Hose. 4.11.
               and strong drinke doe take away (and as it were forstale) the heart: meaning therby that riot and vncleannes (the vnseparable companions of beauty, health, & riches, where piety is wanting) do make both men and women so brutish; & blockish that no threatning or iudgments (though neuer so nere their necks) can once enter into their hearts. Had not such then need to be corrected and smitten with the sword of the spirit, which is the word of God,
Hebr. 4.12. that the same beeing quicke and powerfull, sharper then any two edged sword, piercing euen to the deuiding asunder of the soule and spirit, and of the ioints and marrow, may bee vnto them a discerner of the thoughts and intentions of their hearts, they may not

onely bee conuinced in their iudgements of this palpable error in ouerprizing such outward gifts, where godlines is wanting (which was the second vse & profit of this prouerbe) but also reprooued and checked in their owne consciences for their prophane and vngodly conuersation, proceeding from their blind ignorance and errour of opinion? I haue heard (saith the Prophet) Ephraim lamenting, and bewailing himselfe thus;
               Ierem. 31.18.19.
               Thou hast corrected mee that I might bee corrected as an vntamed calfe (or bullock not accustomed to the yoke) conuert thou me, that I may he conuerted, for thou art the Lord my God. Surely after I am conuerted it will repent mee, and after I am instructed I shall smite my selfe vpon the thigh, I blush for shame, and am confounded, because I beare the reproach of my youth.
